Dialogue: 0,0:00:09.00,0:00:18.00,Default,,0,0,0,,20,000 years ago, the world suffered in the depths of the last ice age.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:18.00,0:00:25.00,Default,,0,0,0,,For several thousand years, global average temperatures stayed 15 degrees Fahrenheit,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:25.00,0:00:30.00,Default,,0,0,0,,that's about 8 degrees celcius below what they're today,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:30.00,0:00:40.00,Default,,0,0,0,,and mile thick glaciers covered much of North America, Europe, and Asia;
Dialogue: 0,0:00:40.00,0:00:50.00,Default,,0,0,0,,outside the ice-covered regions, it was so dry that survival became difficult in most areas.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:50.00,0:00:57.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Some areas where people'd been living became inhospitable,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:57.00,0:01:07.00,Default,,0,0,0,,and in some other places, new barriers of ice or desert separated groups of people,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:07.00,0:01:19.00,Default,,0,0,0,,but against all odds, some people found ways to survive in severe conditions as far north as Siberia.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:19.00,0:01:25.00,Default,,0,0,0,,The ice age not only created barriers, it also created bridges
Dialogue: 0,0:01:25.00,0:01:31.00,Default,,0,0,0,,with so much water locked up in ice, sea levels dropped,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:31.00,0:01:38.00,Default,,0,0,0,,exposing land and connected Siberia and Alaska,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:38.00,0:01:42.00,Default,,0,0,0,,a few people in Siberia took advantage of this bridge,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:42.00,0:01:50.00,Default,,0,0,0,,moving into present-day Alaska, and later, down into other parts of North America,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:50.00,0:01:55.40,Default,,0,0,0,,maybe they followed migrating herds
Dialogue: 0,0:01:57.00,0:02:04.04,Default,,0,0,0,,or maybe, they traveled in small boats, down the Pacific coast,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:05.00,0:02:08.76,Default,,0,0,0,,or maybe they did both.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:10.00,0:02:12.00,Default,,0,0,0,,No matter how they got there,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:12.00,0:02:20.00,Default,,0,0,0,,those people who get there became the ancestors of today's Americans.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:20.00,0:02:28.00,Default,,0,0,0,,In just a short time, humans from a small corner of Africa had populated all continents
Dialogue: 0,0:02:28.00,0:02:30.00,Default,,0,0,0,,except Antarctica,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:30.00,0:02:42.00,Default,,0,0,0,,and in there new homes, their languages began to differentiate to form the precursors of today's languages.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:42.00,0:02:46.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Some populations probably didn't survived the ice age
Dialogue: 0,0:02:46.00,0:02:54.00,Default,,0,0,0,,and those that did often became more isolated from other groups,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:54.00,0:02:58.00,Default,,0,0,0,,scattered around the world, these small populations
Dialogue: 0,0:02:58.00,0:03:08.00,Default,,0,0,0,,became more being culturally, and genetically distinct from one another.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:08.00,0:03:12.00,Default,,0,0,0,,How would cultural innovations helped a few of these groups
Dialogue: 0,0:03:12.00,0:03:17.51,Default,,0,0,0,,to expand dramatically over the next several thousands years.
